==Media==
===Anime===
An original anime television adaption has been announced, Hiroshi Nishikiori directed the series at [[J.C.Staff]] with scripts written by Takao Yoshioka and Mizuto Suzuki and Kengo Tokusashi produced the music at Square Enix.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-10-24/square-enix-schoolgirl-strikers-game-app-gets-tv-anime-by-j.c-staff/.108029|title=Square Enix's Schoolgirl Strikers Game App Gets TV Anime by J.C. Staff|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=October 24, 2016|accessdate=October 24, 2016}}</ref> The anime aired between January 7 to April 1, 2017 on [[Tokyo MX]] with further broadcasting on [[Nippon Broadcasting System|BS11]], [[AT-X (company)|AT-X]], [[Kyoto Broadcasting System|KBS]], and [[Sun Television|Sun TV]]; [[Crunchyroll]] streamed the anime.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-01-05/crunchyroll-streams-schoolgirl-strikers-animation-channel-tv-anime/.110641|title=Crunchyroll Streams Schoolgirl Strikers Animation Channel TV Anime|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=January 5, 2017|accessdate=January 5, 2016}}</ref> The series ran for 13 episodes and released across seven BD/DVD volumes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sgs-anime.com/bd_dvd/vol7/|title=BD/DVD}}</ref>

